<p>
Hopefully I'm not the only one who obsessively tries to abide by the
high codes of good practice and writes descriptive documentation on
every last <a href="http://bruce-connor.github.io/emacs-online-documentation/Fun/defun"><code>defun</code></a> or <a href="http://bruce-connor.github.io/emacs-online-documentation/Fun/defcustom"><code>defcustom</code></a>. If so, I can't be the only one who
has grown tired of typing ` then ' inside Emacs doc strings.
</p>
<div class="highlight"><pre><code class="language-cl" data-lang="cl"><span class="p">(</span><span class="nv">define-key</span> <span class="nv">emacs-lisp-mode-map</span> <span class="s">&quot;\C-cm&quot;</span> <span class="s">&quot;`&#39;\C-b&quot;</span><span class="p">)</span></code></pre></div>
<p>
The <kbd>m</kbd> key feels natural to me here, because I also
use <kbd>C-c m</kbd> in LaTeX for quoting math, but you might
find some other key more intuitive.
</p>

